title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0001
text: Which package contains the NavigableSet interface?
explanation: The NavigableSet interface is part of the java.util package.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0002
text: Which interface does NavigableSet extend?
explanation: The NavigableSet interface extends the SortedSet interface.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0003
text: What is the main characteristic of a NavigableSet?

options.text: It provides navigation methods for closest matches

explanation: NavigableSet provides navigation methods to find closest matches for elements.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0004
text: Which of the following classes implements the NavigableSet interface?
explanation: TreeSet is the main implementation of the NavigableSet interface.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0005
text: Which of the following methods returns the greatest element less than the given element?
explanation: The lower(E e) method returns the greatest element strictly less than the given element.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0006
text: Which of the following methods returns the greatest element less than or equal to the given element?
explanation: The floor(E e) method returns the greatest element less than or equal to the given element.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0007
text: Which of the following methods returns the least element greater than or equal to the given element?
explanation: The ceiling(E e) method returns the least element greater than or equal to the given element.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0008
text: Which of the following methods returns the least element strictly greater than the given element?
explanation: The higher(E e) method returns the least element strictly greater than the given element.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0009
text: Which of the following methods retrieves and removes the first element of the set?
explanation: The pollFirst() method retrieves and removes the first element of the set, or returns null if empty.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0010
text: Which of the following methods retrieves and removes the last element of the set?
explanation: The pollLast() method retrieves and removes the last element of the set, or returns null if empty.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0011
text: Which of the following methods returns a reverse order view of the set?
explanation: The descendingSet() method returns a reverse order view of the elements in the set.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0012
text: Which of the following methods returns an iterator over the elements in descending order?
explanation: The descendingIterator() method returns an iterator that traverses the set in descending order.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0013
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and duplicates?

options.text: NavigableSet does not allow duplicate elements

explanation: NavigableSet does not allow duplicate elements, just like Set and SortedSet.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0014
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and null elements?

options.text: TreeSet does not allow null elements

explanation: TreeSet, the main implementation of NavigableSet, does not allow null elements because it uses natural ordering.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0015
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and ordering?

options.text: NavigableSet maintains elements in ascending order by default

explanation: NavigableSet maintains elements in ascending order by default.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0016
text: Which of the following methods returns a view of the portion of the set less than a given element?
explanation: The headSet(E toElement, boolean inclusive) method returns a view of the portion of the set less than the given element.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0017
text: Which of the following methods returns a view of the portion of the set greater than a given element?
explanation: The tailSet(E fromElement, boolean inclusive) method returns a view of the portion of the set greater than the given element.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0018
text: Which of the following methods returns a view of the portion of the set between two elements?

options.text: subSet(E fromElement, boolean fromInclusive, E toElement, boolean toInclusive)

explanation: The subSet(E fromElement, boolean fromInclusive, E toElement, boolean toInclusive) method returns a view of the portion of the set between two elements.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0019
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and comparator?

options.text: A custom Comparator can define the sorting order
Comparator cannot be used with NavigableSet
Comparator is used only for duplicates

explanation: A custom Comparator can be provided to define the sorting order of elements in a NavigableSet.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0020
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and natural ordering?

options.text: If no comparator is provided, natural ordering is used
Natural ordering is used only for duplicates

explanation: If no comparator is provided, NavigableSet uses the natural ordering of its elements.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0021
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and descendingSet()?

options.text: descendingSet() returns a reverse order view of the set

explanation: The descendingSet() method returns a reverse order view of the elements in the set.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0022
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and descendingIterator()?

options.text: descendingIterator() iterates elements in reverse order
descendingIterator() iterates elements in insertion order

explanation: The descendingIterator() method iterates elements in reverse order.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0023
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and pollFirst()?

options.text: pollFirst() retrieves and removes the first element
pollFirst() retrieves but does not remove the first element

explanation: The pollFirst() method retrieves and removes the first element of the set.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0024
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and pollLast()?

options.text: pollLast() retrieves and removes the last element
pollLast() retrieves but does not remove the last element

explanation: The pollLast() method retrieves and removes the last element of the set.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0025
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and lower(E e)?

options.text: lower(E e) returns the greatest element less than the given element
lower(E e) returns the smallest element greater than the given element
lower(E e) removes the given element

explanation: The lower(E e) method returns the greatest element strictly less than the given element.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0026
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and floor(E e)?

options.text: floor(E e) returns the greatest element less than or equal to the given element
floor(E e) returns the smallest element greater than the given element
floor(E e) removes the given element

explanation: The floor(E e) method returns the greatest element less than or equal to the given element.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0027
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and ceiling(E e)?

options.text: ceiling(E e) returns the least element greater than or equal to the given element
ceiling(E e) returns the greatest element less than the given element
ceiling(E e) removes the given element

explanation: The ceiling(E e) method returns the least element greater than or equal to the given element.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0028
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and higher(E e)?

options.text: higher(E e) returns the least element greater than the given element
higher(E e) returns the greatest element less than the given element
higher(E e) removes the given element

explanation: The higher(E e) method returns the least element strictly greater than the given element.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0029
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and subSet()?

options.text: subSet() returns a view between two elements with inclusivity options

explanation: The subSet() method returns a view between two elements with options for inclusivity.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0030
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and headSet()?

options.text: headSet() returns elements less than a given element with inclusivity option
headSet() returns elements greater than a given element

explanation: The headSet() method returns elements less than a given element with an option to include the boundary.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0031
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and tailSet()?

options.text: tailSet() returns elements greater than or equal to a given element with inclusivity option
tailSet() returns elements less than a given element

explanation: The tailSet() method returns elements greater than or equal to a given element with an option to include the boundary.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0032
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and comparator()?

options.text: comparator() returns null if natural ordering is used
comparator() throws exception if no comparator

explanation: If natural ordering is used, comparator() returns null.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0033
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and TreeSet?
explanation: TreeSet implements the NavigableSet interface.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0034
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and synchronization?

options.text: NavigableSet is not synchronized by default

explanation: NavigableSet is not synchronized by default; synchronization can be achieved using Collections.synchronizedNavigableSet().

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0035
text: Which of the following methods can be used to synchronize a NavigableSet?
explanation: The Collections.synchronizedNavigableSet() method returns a synchronized (thread-safe) navigable set.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0036
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and fail-fast behavior?

options.text: Iterators of most NavigableSet implementations are fail-fast

explanation: Iterators of most NavigableSet implementations are fail-fast and throw ConcurrentModificationException if modified during iteration.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0037
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and descending order iteration?

options.text: descendingIterator() iterates elements in reverse order
descendingIterator() iterates elements in insertion order

explanation: The descendingIterator() method iterates elements in reverse order.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0038
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and comparator chaining?

options.text: Comparator chaining allows multiple comparison criteria
Comparator chaining is used for synchronization

explanation: Comparator chaining allows multiple comparison criteria using methods like thenComparing().

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0039
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and immutability?

options.text: NavigableSet can be made unmodifiable using Collections.unmodifiableNavigableSet()

explanation: NavigableSet can be made unmodifiable using the Collections.unmodifiableNavigableSet() method.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0040
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and TreeSet performance?

options.text: TreeSet provides O(log n) performance for basic operations

explanation: TreeSet provides O(log n) performance for add, remove, and contains operations.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0041
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and null elements?

options.text: TreeSet does not allow null elements

explanation: TreeSet does not allow null elements because it uses natural ordering or a comparator.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0042
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and ordering?

options.text: NavigableSet maintains elements in ascending order by default

explanation: NavigableSet maintains elements in ascending order by default.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0043
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and fail-fast iterators?
explanation: Fail-fast iterators throw ConcurrentModificationException if the set is modified during iteration.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0044
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and comparator() return value?

options.text: Returns null if natural ordering is used

explanation: If natural ordering is used, comparator() returns null.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0045
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and duplicates?

options.text: NavigableSet does not allow duplicate elements

explanation: NavigableSet does not allow duplicate elements, just like Set and SortedSet.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0046
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and comparator chaining?

options.text: Comparator chaining allows multiple comparison criteria
Comparator chaining is used for synchronization

explanation: Comparator chaining allows multiple comparison criteria using methods like thenComparing().

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0047
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and TreeSet synchronization?

options.text: TreeSet is not synchronized by default

explanation: TreeSet is not synchronized by default; synchronization can be achieved using Collections.synchronizedNavigableSet().

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0048
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and comparator()?

options.text: comparator() returns null if natural ordering is used
comparator() throws exception if no comparator

explanation: If natural ordering is used, comparator() returns null.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0049
text: Which of the following is true about NavigableSet and iteration order?

options.text: Iteration follows ascending order by default

explanation: Iteration over a NavigableSet follows ascending order by default.

title: JavaCollectionsFrameworkNavigableSet - Q0050
text: Which of the following best describes the NavigableSet interface?

options.text: A set that maintains elements in sorted order and provides navigation methods
A set that maintains insertion order
A set that allows duplicate elements
A set that stores elements randomly

explanation: The NavigableSet interface represents a set that maintains elements in sorted order and provides navigation methods.
